question:
"All three passages discuss issues associated with winter, although the issues are different-- ranging from dealing with the natural elements in the winter to wintertime holidays. 

In your opinion, which passage has the most severe and troubling conflict? In your response, be sure to summarize and compare the problems shown in each story excerpt. "
rationale: The compare-and-contrast essay topics included in the open-ended questions are a unique portion of our Squiggle Park: Dreamscape platform. The typical multiple-choice questions that students see in standard gameplay require them to respond based on one reading passage. However, these open-ended responses will prepare students to engage in the literary skill known as synthesizing.

question: Both of these passages end off on a cliffhanger, leaving readers to predict what might happen next. Pick one of the story excerpts and write an original ending of your own. Write the next two paragraphs of one of the stories, describing whats you imagine would happen next. Try to match the writing style of the author.
rationale: The passage questions require students to do a great deal of inferring. This entire assignment would be a great assignment for students who have difficulty predicting, inferring, or extending themselves beyond what is directly written.

question: Some of the story excerpts that you just read communicate a mood of urgency and danger. Write an essay in which you identify the passages that have an urgent mood and analyze the techniques the authors used to develop the mood.
rationale: Identifying mood is a topic that students likely have practiced in or before sixth grade, but students will experience more rigorous challengs as they will be required to identify authors' techniques themselves (which could be character development [like dialogue or characters' actions] or figurative language [which was commonly used in "The Great Glowing Forest" and is the topic of many of the MC questions for this topic]).

question: Which of the passages address the big idea of responding to enemies? In two paragraphs, identify which passages best address the main idea. Provide textual evidence to prove your point, and analyze how these passages relate to the idea of reacting to enemies.
rationale: Both "Shortest War Ever" and "King Tut's Sandals" touch on the topic of enemies. This similar idea can serve as a commonality as students compare and contrast the texts. Given that it is such a broad idea, students will have to work independently to find textual evidence that can be used to further elaborate on the similarity.

question: The two passages in this assignment are from the same story, but they are told from differing points of view. From what perspective is the first passage told? Who is the narrator of the second passage? Explain who appears to be narrating each passage, and why changing narrators may be useful in a story.
rationale: Very few point-of-view questions according to a recent audit done by Geoffrey.

question: Time period is an important part of the setting of a story. Write a paragraph in which you determine if each of the following passages is set in the past, present, or future. Use textual evidence and any background information you know to help you explain the settings you chose for each passage.
rationale: While students in early elementary school have a background in identify the setting's physical location, placing a passage within a time period (ie., past or present, or even a specific historical era) can be more challenging. This assignment requires students to look for clues to the time period and apply (or develop) their background knowledge to determine time periods for text.

question: All three of the passages are examples of fantasy stories. Write a response in which you explain what aspects of each story causes it to be classified as fantasy. Be sure to include textual evidence.
rationale: While students in grade 5 likely can identify the genre of a passage, this open-ended question requires students to provide evidence as to why a passage best falls within a specific genre. This will require students to make note of stylistic plot elements, the usage of certain settings, and character archetypes in order to draw similarities between common writing structures and genre.

question:
"All three of the passages communicate themes. In your opinion, which passage communicates the most important lesson? Why?

In your response, identify the passage and its theme, providing textual evidence to support the theme. Also be sure to explain why you think the lesson from this passage is more important than the themes given in the other stories."
rationale: This open-ended question is similar to the advanced one, which students may have completed. However, it requires them to not only identify the themes, but also evaluate them.

question: All three of the passages communicate themes. Write a response in which you identify the themes of each passage and provide textual evidence as support.
rationale: Being able to identify the themes, or lessons, within literature is a commonly practiced skill in upper-elementary grades. Introducing students to this skill will be beneficial, as students determine and evaluate thematic elements of stories all the way into collegiate settings.

question: All three of the passages communicate a different mood. Write a response in which you identify the mood of each passage and provide textual evidence as support.
rationale: There are mood questions within the passages, which should provide students with scaffolding as they work to determine the moods (as well as relevant textual evidence, for each.

question: The passages "Don't Wake The Giant" and "Dangerous Beasts" both end off on cliffhangers, leaving readers to predict what might happen next. Pick one of the story excerpts and write an original ending of your own. Write the next paragraphs of one of the stories, describing whats you imagine would happen next.
rationale: The passage questions require students to closely read very short passage and derive meaning for single sentences. This entire assignment would be a great assignment for students who have difficulty predicting, inferring, or extending themselves beyond what is directly written.

question: Both of these passages focus on the big idea of communication. How is communication shown in each passage? Do the authors share any themes, or lessons, about communication in their passages? Explain in 5-7 sentences.
rationale: The passages are already difficult enough that reading and responding to two passages would likely take students the bulk of the testing time.

question:
"Of the three passages, which two are the most similar? What similiarities did you notice between the two passages?

Be sure to consider the passages' problems, characters, settings, and solutions. "
rationale:
"This passage also has a high failure rating (77.67%).

It involves characters observing an unfamiliar creature, just like in ""Captain Critter."""

question: At the end of both "Food Chain" and "The Fox and the Rabbit," characters act in surprising ways that are not like how they would act usually. What do the characters do that is surprising or unexpected? Why does each character act in an unexpected way? Write a response that contains 4-5 sentences. Be sure to explain the rabbit's behavior and the bear's behavior.
rationale:
"The easiest test has 11 questions in total.

This test will have 18 questions, even though it only has two passages. There is no need for a third passage, since the difficulty has always increased by including more questions. "

question: Based on what you have read in "The Founding of the United States" and in "Canada's Founding," which country has a longer official history? How can you tell?
rationale: For the easiest test, no third passage will be included to limit the cognitive load on students under a time constraint.

question: In the passages "Chasing Yao" and "White Fang #2," the settings of the passages are never clearly stated. However, there are many clues that readers can use to try to determine the passages' settings. Where and when do these passages most likely take place? Write a response in which you identify text evidence that includes hints about the settings of the passages, as well as make inferences about the settings.

After reading the three passages, write a response in which you list some of the things people should and should NOT do in order to stay healthy. Use the information and the characters from the passages as inspiration.

In the stories "Pukey" and "Ice Cream Dream," some of the characters make decisions that could lead to them either spreading germs or not feeling well themselves. Write a summary in which you identify the characters who make poor decisions, as well as how they put the health of themselves or others at risk.

In both of these passages, characters cope with feeling as if they have been placed outside of their comfort zones. Write a response in which you explain how this idea relates to each passage. Be sure to include textual evidence in your response.

All of these passages are set in time periods where people dealt with hardships. Write a response in which you identify the approximate time period of each passage and explain the hardships or struggles that individuals seeked to overcome. Be sure to include textual evidence.
What word would you use to describe the mood of all three stories? Tell how it fits each story.
Which story do you think is the spookiest? Why? What makes you think that?

The story "Kitchen Witch" uses three strategies to add suspense to the story:
1. repetition (repeating a sentence over and over)
2. rhetorical questions (the narrator asking herself a question)
3. ellipses (the '...' puncutation mark used to make a long pause)

For your response, write the next paragraph of either "Followed" or "Transformation." Continue the story and tell what happens next! Use repetition, rhetorical questions, or ellipses in your response.

If the author of these four stories could give you advice, do you think she would tell you to explore things you find curious or to stay away from strange items and people? Why? Support your answer with examples from the stories.

In both "The Rattling Coffin" and "Mutant Mrs. Finnegan," the main characters witness events that leave them feeling strong emotions. What emotion do the characters feel? How would readers most likely feel after reading these passages? Write a response in which you identify the characters' emotions and the mood of the passages.

The story "Digging" has what is called a circular ending, which means the end of the story is very similar to the beginning (both the first paragraph and the last paragraph describe the sound of digging, both even using the word "CLANG!"). 

Write a two- or three-paragraph response in which you continue the story that started in "Scary Basement." As you write the rest of the story, try to end with a circular ending by having the basement door open again at the end of the story.
Two of the stories show how brothers and sisters act when they spend time together. Write an answer that retells if the brothers and sisters got along with each other.

How is Grayson's relationship with his siblings different from Nelson's relationship with his sister? Write a response in which you contrast the sibling relationships shown in "Banana Pancakes" and "Spaceship Kid."
Out of all the characters included in the three stories, which character most acts like a role model? What makes you think this? Support your answer with textual evidence.
Each of these stories features a character dealing with a personal conflict. Which story contains the most complex conflict? Why? What factors make the problem difficult for the character to solve?
Do you think John or Kayla has nicer friends? Why?
